data.content:
In xUnit, the mapping is:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|-------|-------|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` with a shared fixture |

Here's your converted class:

```csharp
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        // Per-test setup (runs before each test)
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        // Per-test teardown (runs after each test)
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key points:
- xUnit creates a **new instance** per test, so the constructor/`Dispose` replaces `[SetUp]`/`[TearDown]`.
- `IClassFixture<T>` shares one fixture instance across all tests in the class — replacing `[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]`.
- The fixture is injected via the constructor parameter.
